  (α₁+2α₂) ≡ 6 (mod 7): 2640

H mod 7 distribution at n=6: {1: 7248, 2: 9440, 3: 4320, 4: 2880, 5: 6240, 6: 2640}
H ≡ 0 (mod 7): 0 tournaments

======================================================================
  PART 4: UNIFIED FORBIDDEN RESIDUE
======================================================================

THEOREM (n=5): Both forbidden residues trace to α₁=3 impossible.

H ≡ 2 (mod 5): requires α₁ ≡ 3 (mod 5) → needs α₁=3 → IMPOSSIBLE
H ≡ 0 (mod 7): requires α₁ ≡ 3 (mod 7) → needs α₁=3 → IMPOSSIBLE

The number 3 is the COMMON OBSTRUCTION.
Why can't α₁ = dc3 + dc5 = 3?

The (dc3, dc5) pairs achievable at n=5:
  (0,0), (1,0), (2,0), (3,1), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3), (5,2)

The gap: no pair sums to 3.
  To get α₁=3: need (0,3),(1,2),(2,1),(3,0)
  But (3,0) doesn't exist: dc3=3 forces dc5≥1
  And (2,1),(1,2),(0,3) don't exist either

DEEPER: dc3=3 requires score sequence (1,1,2,3,3).
Every tournament with scores (1,1,2,3,3) has dc5≥1.
This is because the 3-cycle structure at dc3=3 forces a 5-cycle.

PROVING dc3=3 → dc5≥1 at n=5:

  Score (1,1,2,3,3): 240/240 have dc5>0
  Score (0, 1, 3, 3, 3), dc3=1: 40 have dc5=0, 0 have dc5>0
  Score (0, 2, 2, 2, 4), dc3=1: 40 have dc5=0, 0 have dc5>0
  Score (0, 2, 2, 3, 3), dc3=2: 120 have dc5=0, 0 have dc5>0
  Score (1, 1, 1, 3, 4), dc3=1: 40 have dc5=0, 0 have dc5>0
  Score (1, 1, 2, 2, 4), dc3=2: 120 have dc5=0, 0 have dc5>0
  Score (1, 1, 2, 3, 3), dc3=3: 0 have dc5=0, 240 have dc5>0

======================================================================
  PART 5: 5 AS THE CRITICAL MODULUS
======================================================================

The forbidden residues at n=5:
  mod 2: H ≡ 0 forbidden (Rédei, universal)
  mod 3: none forbidden (all residues appear)
  mod 5: H ≡ 2 forbidden (α₁=3 impossible)
  mod 7: H ≡ 0 forbidden (α₁=3 impossible)

For n=6:
  mod 2: H ≡ 0 forbidden (Rédei, universal)
  mod 3: none
  mod 5: none (α₁=3 becomes achievable)
  mod 7: H ≡ 0 forbidden (persists!)

KEY INSIGHT: 5 'loses' its forbidden residue at n=6
because new (dc3,dc5) pairs become achievable.
But 7 retains its forbidden residue!

Why? H ≡ 0 (mod 7) requires α₁+2α₂ ≡ 3 (mod 7).
At n=6, the range of α₁+2α₂ may still miss 3 (mod 7).

α₁ + 2α₂ values at n=6: [0, 1, 2, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 20, 21, 22]
α₁ + 2α₂ mod 7: [0, 1, 2, 4, 5, 6]

======================================================================
  PART 6: H mod 35 (= 5·7)
======================================================================

Since 5 and 7 are coprime, H mod 35 = CRT(H mod 5, H mod 7)
At n=5: H ∈ {1,3,5,9,11,13,15}
  H mod 35: [1, 3, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15]
  Missing mod 35: [7, 17, 19, 21, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 33]
  (only odd values possible by Rédei)

At n=6: H mod 35 residues: [1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 8, 9, 10, 11, 13, 15, 17, 19, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 33]
  Missing odd residues mod 35: [7, 21]

======================================================================
  PART 7: FIVE AS DISCRIMINANT — FIBONACCI IN H
======================================================================

The Fibonacci sequence mod p has Pisano period π(p).
The key connection to tournaments:

H = 1 + 2α₁ + 4α₂ + 8α₃ + ...
  = I(CG, 2) = Σ_{k≥0} i_k · 2^k
where i_k = #{independent sets of size k in CG}

The powers of 2 modulo p cycle with period ord_p(2):
  ord_3(2) = 2
  ord_5(2) = 4
  ord_7(2) = 3
  ord_11(2) = 10
  ord_13(2) = 12

At p=5: ord_5(2) = 4
  2^0=1, 2^1=2, 2^2=4, 2^3=3, 2^4=1 (mod 5)
  H mod 5 = i_0 + 2i_1 + 4i_2 + 3i_3 + i_4 + 2i_5 + ...
  = Σ_k i_k · 2^k mod 5

This is evaluating the independence polynomial at x=2 mod 5.
And 2 mod 5 = 2 is the PRIMITIVE root mod 5!
(ord_5(2) = 4 = φ(5) = Euler's totient)

So 2 is a PRIMITIVE ROOT mod 5,
which means evaluating I(CG, 2) mod 5 = evaluating at a generator,
which captures the FULL mod-5 structure of the independence polynomial.

This is why 5 plays a special role: it's the smallest odd prime
for which 2 is a primitive root AND which equals the Fibonacci discriminant.

Primes where 2 is a primitive root:
  p=3: ord_3(2) = 2 = p-1 ✓
  p=5: ord_5(2) = 4 = p-1 ✓
  p=11: ord_11(2) = 10 = p-1 ✓
  p=13: ord_13(2) = 12 = p-1 ✓
  p=19: ord_19(2) = 18 = p-1 ✓
  p=29: ord_29(2) = 28 = p-1 ✓
  p=37: ord_37(2) = 36 = p-1 ✓

These are: [3, 5, 11, 13, 19, 29, 37]
(Related to Artin's conjecture on primitive roots)

Done.
